      "video_url": null,
      "description": "The Noon Optimist Club of Marshall met Wednesday, Oct. 2 in Hutchins Hall of the Cumberland Presbyterian Church. We enjoyed a taco bar from Jucy’s. Our thanks to Optimists Le Ila and Charles Dixon for picking up the food and...",
      "content": "The Noon Optimist Club of Marshall met Wednesday, Oct. 2 in Hutchins Hall of the Cumberland Presbyterian Church. We enjoyed a taco bar from Jucy’s. Our thanks to Optimists Le Ila and Charles Dixon for picking up the food and to Le Ila for providing pumpkin spice cakes for dessert (one a bundt ring and the other in the shape of a pumpkin with vines and leaves made of fondant! President Julie Brock called on Optimist Le Ila for the opening prayer and then led in the pledge to the flag and Optimist Creed. President Julie then welcomed the Young Texans, their families and Marshall High School school administrators, Principal Mike Miller and Associate Principal Carolyn Oliver. She explained that all the 2024-25 Young Texans had a chance at receiving one of the $500 grants awarded at random to three of the Texannes and three of the Texans at the end of year awards assembly. Optimist Julie then introduced Jiya Mistry as the Young Texanne for October. Her favorite classes are focused on healthcare. “I love science classes and any healthcare career and technical education classes — med. micro, certified clinical medical assistant.” Her favorite teachers are Erica Wilson for English language arts, Anna Day for health science, Jana Duck for algebra II and Skylyn Potts for biology. Her grade point average is 5.489. Jiya is active in extra-curricular activities such as Student Council, National Honor Society (where she serves as secretary), the senior class (where she serves as vice president), and the Interact Club (where she serves as historian). She has been on the varsity volleyball team for four years and “so far for three years” has participated in powerlifting (her top lift weight is 300 pounds!). In the area of religion, she said, “I am Hindu, so I do believe in numerous religious activities such as Garba, Diwali and many more.” Optimist Richard Magrill said that he was familiar with Diwali, a time for religious rituals and sharing traditional stories and also an opportunity to spruce up the home, buy new clothes, and, of course, enjoy parties, feasting and an exchange of gifts. (For Hindus, Diwali is linked to the ancient legend of Lord Rama, who was deprived of his kingdom and sent into exile for 14 years. It celebrates Rama’s eventual defeat of the evil spirit Ravana, and his triumphant return to his home.) However, he asked about Garba? As it turns out Garba is a nine-day festival that is not easy to give a short answer to! It is a dance that honors, worships and celebrates the feminine form of divinity. “Each day a different goddess is emphasized,” explained Shilpa Mistry. Intrigued, Optimist Richard went to Wikipedia for a little more information. “Traditionally, the dance is performed by women in a circle around a clay lantern with a light inside. The vessel itself is a symbol of the body, within whom divinity (in the form of the Goddess or Devi) resides. Garba is danced around this symbol to honor the fact that all humans have the divine energy of Devi within them. “Garba is performed in a circle (concentric circles when there are many people). The circle represents the Hindu view of time. In Hinduism, time is cyclical. As the cycle of time revolves, from birth to life to death to rebirth, the only thing that is constant is the Goddess, an unmoving symbol in the midst of all of this unending and infinite movement. The dance symbolizes that God, represented in feminine form in this case, is the only thing that remains unchanging in a constantly changing universe (jagat).” Jiya is also an artist in acrylic painting and in sketching. She won three awards during her freshman year. Asked what she most likes to paint, she replied that she liked nature, landscapes and flowers. “I mostly paint from my imagination,” she shared. Her goals include graduating from MHS and then attending college. “I am undecided as of right now between Baylor University, Texas A&M University or the University of Texas at Austin. Wherever, I end up, I plan to major in biology and attend medical school to become a cardiologist.” Optimist Melissa Al-Amadhi thanked her for choosing cardiology, as did Optimists Richard Magrill and Le Ila Dixon. She shared that her interest was sparked by the medical condition of her little sister, Nishta. In a personal message to her parents, Mukund and Shilpa Mistry, she said: “Thank you for every sacrifice, support and always be there for me, whether it is the smallest thing or the biggest, you guys are always there for me no matter the situation. From Private School Interscholastic Activity, to volleyball to power lifting and all of my academic related accomplishments, you both have been present. Thank you for always being there. I love you guys so much! I am so proud to be your daughter.” President Julie then introduced Gavin Carlisle as the Young Texan for October. His favorite subject is chemistry and his favorite teachers are Janna Duck for algebra II, Glenda Bailey for business finance, Michael Wheeler for science, Golf Coach Casey Broadus and 12th Grade Counselor Kelley Paul. His grade point average is 5.167. Gavin is active in varsity golf, the National Honor Society and the Fellowship of Christian Athletes. (He is captain of the golf team!) He enjoys bass fishing (with a buddy in Fern Lake) and deer, dove and hog hunting. Optimist Le Ila asked if he and his hunting buddies “eat what they kill.” He said, “Yes, but not the hogs; they are usually too tough. However, they don’t go to waste. There is a coyote problem, so the hog carcasses are used as bait for the coyotes!” He works at Marshall Mercantile, “doing whatever is needed.” “It’s a great place to work!” In response to questions, he reported that the ice cream parlor is now open with vanilla, chocolate and strawberry on offer. “Come by and have some,” he advised. As far as college is concerned, he is leaning toward the University of Arkansas but may end up someplace else. He plans to major in finance. In a personal message to his parents, Scott and Tracy Carlile, he said: “To my mom and dad, thank y’all so much for all of the unwavering support whether it was with school, golf, baseball and everything else. I wouldn’t have been able to do it without y’all. I love y’all so much,” and added, “have fun dealing with Ian [his younger brother] over the next four years” in recognition that he’s not leaving them with an empty nest! As promised, President Julie gave new MHS Principal Mike Miller the opportunity to introduce himself. He indicated that he began his career as an educator as a band director before moving into administration. This is his first year in Marshall. Due to various issues, his family is still in the house in Arp, but he is glad to be here in his new work. “It’s really great to be in a town where the community is so supportive of the schools!” he said. He reported on the progress and anticipated completion of the various physical improvements at the high school/junior high school campus. Total high school enrollment this year now stands at 1,477, and there are approximately 350 in the senior class. The Optimists gave the Young Texans and school administrators a round of applause. President Julie presented pots of large-petalled yellow and orange fall mums to the mothers and Optimist John Fortune took pictures. Note: John takes pictures throughout the meeting and President Julie shares these with the families.",
