      "content": "THE three-year fraud probe into SNP finances threatens to derail the next Holyrood election, the whistleblower who sparked the probe warns. Independence campaigner Sean Clerkin says “delays” in winding up the long-running case could influence voters at the next ballot expected to be held in May 2026. 2 Political activist Sean Clerkin has made the shock claims 2 Police outside former FM Sturgeon's house near Glasgow He also raised concerns the indy movement could be irreparably damaged by the Operation Branchform saga. Mr Clerkin says he has received death threats from Nats after raising the alarm about £600,000 which had been raised for a second referendum on leaving the UK . He said: “All these years down the line I have been persecuted by nationalists who have persecuted me on social media and at rallies. “Threatening to do me in, threatened to take me out and I have had death threats. Read more Scottish news FIEND'S MOVE Alesha MacPhail’s killer Aaron Campbell will finally be moved to an adult jail BOOZE PROBE easyJet axes five cabin crew over 'boozy misconduct' at Egypt hotel nightclub “This case has to be wound up by the end of this year. “For us to have free and fair elections in 2026 without this hanging over any of the pro-independence parties.” Police raided the house of former First Minister Nicola Sturgeon and her ex-SNP chief executive husband Peter Murrell amid concerns the cash had gone missing in April last year. He has been charged with embezzlement, while she was arrested by released without charge. Most read in The Scottish Sun CITY HORROR Major incident as black cab ploughs into 3 shoppers on busy Glasgow street EVIL NEXT DOOR Killer neighbour stabbed fiance 17 times in bins row... before chilling taunt MONEY CHAOS Major banking app down leaving thousands unable to access accounts CELL DRAMA 'Iceman' Stevenson furious after stepson lieutenant 'broke rank' causing bust-up The Crown Office has not revealed when or if they intend to bring him to court . A spokesman said: “Before deciding what action to take, if any, in the public interest, prosecutors will consider if there is enough evidence. “There must be evidence from at least two separate sources to establish that a crime was committed and that the person under investigation was the perpetrator.” Alex Salmond insists Scottish Independence will happen within 10 years Police have defended the investigation timeframe — insisting it has “moved beyond” the initial complaint. An SNP spokesman said: “While the police investigation has reportedly been completed and passed over to the Crown Office, the case remains active and it would be inappropriate to comment.”",
