      "description": "Manchester Airport confirmed that all its security procedures were correctly followed and that the issue occurred at the airline gate. They added police are investigating the matter",
      "content": "EasyJet has launched an investigation after a man managed to board a flight at Manchester Airport without the proper paperwork. It remains unclear whether he had a boarding pass for another flight or no boarding pass at all. The airline is currently trying to figure out how the man was able to get on the flight, but declined to provide any additional details as the investigation is ongoing. A spokesperson simply stated that the man had \"incorrectly boarded\". However, passengers on the flight believe the man didn't have a boarding pass, referring to the incident as a \"security breach\". It's believed the flight to Milan, Italy, was already on the runway preparing for take-off when easyJet cabin crew realised the man shouldn't have been onboard. Manchester Airport confirmed that all its security procedures were correctly followed and that the issue occurred at the airline gate. They added police are investigating the matter. Greater Manchester Police revealed that a man in his 20s was arrested and remains in custody today. He's being held on suspicion of secreting himself for the purpose of being carried in an aircraft without consent and intentionally or recklessly causing public nuisance. understands nothing suspicious was found on board. The incident at Terminal One is not being treated as terror-related either. The man hasn't been named. An easyJet spokesperson confirmed: \"easyJet can confirm that flight EZY2127 from Manchester to Milan was subject to additional security checks, in line with procedures, due to a passenger incorrectly boarding the flight. Safety and security is our highest priority and so we will now work with our ground partner at Manchester Airport to understand how he was able to board the flight.\" A traveller reported that cops boarded the flight and searched the plane. The man was escorted off by officers, while stunned passengers were herded off and had to be re-screened. All bags and carry-ons were rifled through. The journey, on an easyJet jet to Milan Malpensa flight number EZY 2127 was thrown off schedule by the incident. The take-off was slated for 6.23pm last Friday, but the plane didn't leave until 11.10pm. The Airbus touched down in Milan just shy of 2am Saturday landing more than four-and-a-half hours behind because of what happened. Greater Manchester Police said: \"At around 7pm last night (Friday 4 October 2024), we were called to Manchester Airport to reports of a man who had embarked on a flight without the correct documentation. \"On arrival back to the terminal, officers arrested a man in his 20s on suspicion of secreting himself for the purpose of being carried in an aircraft without consent and intentionally or recklessly causing public nuisance. \"He remains in police custody for questioning and enquiries are ongoing.\" No further details have been revealed.",
