      "video_url": null,
      "description": "Changes to Social Security are coming and The Heritage Foundation, a conservative think tank, has proposed raising the retirement age to 70 as a way to improve the program. Rachel Greszler, a senior research fellow at the Roe Institute, advocated for this change in an article for the foundation, suggesting that raising the eligibility age [...]",
      "content": "Changes to Social Security are coming and The Heritage Foundation, a conservative think tank, has proposed raising the retirement age to 70 as a way to improve the program. Rachel Greszler, a senior research fellow at the Roe Institute , advocated for this change in an article for the foundation, suggesting that raising the eligibility age for Social Security benefits could help address the imminent funding crisis facing the Social Security Administration (SSA). The SSA’s 2023 Trustees Report, published earlier this year, warned that the trust funds supporting the largest U.S. benefits program—covering retirees, survivors, and disabled individuals—are set to run out by 2035 unless Congress acts to maintain their solvency. In her article, Greszler suggested gradually raising the normal retirement age from 67 to 69 or 70, with an incremental increase of one or two months each year, tying future changes to life expectancy. According to Greszler, “increased life expectancies, improved healthcare, and the shift away from physically demanding work” imply that many older Americans are now more capable of staying in the workforce longer than before. This, she argued, could help address the looming funding gap in Social Security. She also pointed out that keeping older workers employed could offer advantages beyond merely stabilizing Social Security’s finances. “The benefits of older workers staying in the workforce expand beyond Social Security’s solvency , and the additional income that Americans would earn. Older workers’ wisdom and experience provides an invaluable insight and mentorship to younger workers. And today’s labor market affords increasing opportunities for older workers to gradually ease into retirement, instead of abruptly exiting their careers.” Greszler acknowledged that raising the retirement age alone would not entirely solve the impending financial problems of the Social Security system . Instead, she suggested it could address only about 20 to 30 percent of the shortfall projected by 2035. “While updating Social Security’s retirement age is an important component of reform, it would only solve about 20 percent to 30 percent of the program’s shortfalls. A more accurate inflation adjustment would solve another 20 percent to 25 percent of the program’s shortfalls.” Other experts’ take on the Social Security funding crisis Other experts in Social Security and financial policy do not necessarily agree with the proposal. Stephen Kates, a principal financial analyst with RetireGuide.com , described raising the age of eligibility as “a backwards way of simplifying reducing benefits.” Although not directly commenting on Greszler’s article, Kates pointed out that raising either the earliest eligibility age of 62 or the full retirement age of 67 would mean smaller and delayed benefits for future retirees. He explained that currently, beneficiaries who start taking Social Security at 62 generally see a 30 percent reduction in their monthly payments compared to waiting until the full retirement age of 67 (for those born after 1959). The Center on Budget and Policy Priorities (CBPP) has previously stated that raising the retirement age for Social Security would effectively reduce benefits by an amount similar to the projected benefit cuts expected in the 2030s if no legislative action is taken to secure funding. Zachary Pleat, a senior researcher at Media Matters , also expressed concern over the Heritage Foundation’s proposal. He tied this policy recommendation to a broader political agenda, referencing Project 2025 , an initiative led by the Heritage Foundation, which aims to prepare a conservative coalition for a future administration starting in January 2025. “ The Heritage Foundation , which has played a central role in organizing the planned extremist takeover of the federal government known as Project 2025 for the next Republican president, is now calling for the Social Security retirement age to be raised to 70,” Pleat said. Project 2025 , according to its description, involves a coalition of conservative organizations seeking to ensure that a new conservative administration is ready to govern effectively starting in January 2025. This proposal to raise the Social Security retirement age is viewed by critics as part of a broader ideological push to restructure key government functions and benefits.",
