      "article_id": "1cd03052348e0fe9d07843e73b106f71",
      "title": "Yunus seeks Malaysia's help on Rohingya issue",
      "link": "https://www.manilatimes.net/2024/10/06/world/asia-oceania/yunus-seeks-malaysias-help-on-rohingya-issue/1979732",
      "keywords": [
        "world"
      ],
      "creator": [
        "Associated Press"
      ],
      "video_url": null,
      "description": "DHAKA — Bangladesh's interim leader Muhammad Yunus on Friday sought Malaysia's help in engaging the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (Asean) on raising the issue of repatriating Rohingya refugees to Myanmar.Malaysia takes over the chairmanship of the 10-member regional bloc next year.The appeal came as visiting Malaysian Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim met with Yunus in the Bangladeshi capital Dhaka — the first visit by a foreign leader to the South Asian country since the 2006 Nobel Peace Prize laureate took over on August 8 and the first state visit by a Malaysian leader in 11 years.Yunus took over after former prime minister Sheikh Hasina fled Bangladesh during a mass uprising that accused her of corruption, violation of human rights and excessive use of force against the protesters. He has pledged reforms and a push for reviving the country's troubled economy.Bangladesh has been hosting 1 million Rohingya refugees who fled the violence being committed against them by Myanmar's military. They live in destitute sprawling camps in Bangladesh and have long been demanding a safe return home.Yunus told a news conference after the two leaders held talks that he had asked for Anwar's help in raising the Rohingya repatriation issue at the Asean.\"Malaysia will be supporting us in raising that,\" the interim leader said. \"This is something we have to resolve as soon as possible.\"Yunus said they also discussed boosting bilateral trade and finalizing a free trade agreement between their Muslim-majority nations, as well as political cooperation, investment, and cultural and humanitarian ties.They stressed the need to explore new opportunities in sectors such as agriculture, energy, education, the semiconductor industry and connectivity.Along with involving the Asean in resolving the Rohingya refugee crisis, Bangladesh is also eager to increase trade with members of the bloc. Bangladesh was Malaysia's second-largest trading partner in South Asia in 2023, with total trade reaching $2.78 billion, official figures show.Malaysia is also one of the leading destinations for Bangladeshi migrant workers. About 800,000 Bangladeshi workers are employed as low-skilled employees in Malaysia's construction, manufacturing, plantation and services sectors.But the recruiting process is often corrupt, and allegations of rights violations by Malaysian employers and Bangladeshi recruiting agencies are rampant.Also, more than 6,000 Bangladeshi students study at Malaysian higher education institutions, 2023 figures show.The United News of Bangladesh agency reported that Anwar offered on Friday to recruit 18,000 more new Bangladeshi workers for his country, promising to also ensure decent working conditions for overseas workers.\"We need more workers, but they can't be treated as modern slaves,\" the agency quoted him as saying.Anwar arrived from Pakistan with a 58-member delegation for the hourslong visit to Bangladesh.",
      "content": "DHAKA — Bangladesh's interim leader Muhammad Yunus on Friday sought Malaysia's help in engaging the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (Asean) on raising the issue of repatriating Rohingya refugees to Myanmar. Malaysia takes over the chairmanship of the 10-member regional bloc next year. Register to read this story and more for free . Signing up for an account helps us improve your browsing experience. OR See our subscription options.",
